ChatGPT said:

Alright, this is a serious system, so let’s be surgical. I’ll ask only the questions that actually affect the architecture, not taste or bikeshedding. Think of these as design gates — your answers lock the shape of the controller + FSM.

1️⃣ What is the unit of atomicity inside a run.update?

You’re proposing “actions inside one run.update”, but this must be nailed down:

Q1:
Is an action intended to be:

  • A) a single variable transition (dirty → true, docstatus → 1)

  • B) a semantic user intent (save, submit, cancel)

  • C) both, but with B decomposing into multiple A steps

👉 This decides whether:

  • the FSM lives at the variable level (fine-grained)

  • or at the intent level (Frappe-style)

⚠️ If you answer “both”, we must explicitly separate:

Code
Intent (Save)
  → Action steps
    → Variable transitions

2️⃣ Who is allowed to mutate run.input?

Right now run.input is:

  • UI-driven

  • controller-mutated

  • autosave-mutated

  • potentially FSM-mutated

Q2:
Should only the FSM be allowed to mutate run.input, with:

  • UI → dispatch(action)

  • Controller → fsm.apply(action)

  • No direct writes to run.input

or do you want:

  • mixed mutation (UI + FSM + controller)?

👉 This determines whether run.input is:

  • derived state

  • or authoritative mutable state

⚠️ Mixed mutation = bugs unless very tightly constrained.

3️⃣ Is docstatus a state variable or a derived invariant?

In Frappe:

  • docstatus is not just a field

  • it encodes legal operations

Your FSM treats it as a variable with transitions.

Q3:
Do you want docstatus to be:

  • A) directly transitioned by FSM (transition('docstatus', 1))

  • B) derived from successful actions (submit → docstatus = 1)

  • C) both, but with strict guards

If A, your FSM is the business authority.
If B, your FSM orchestrates, DB confirms.

👉 This affects rollback, retries, and error recovery.

4️⃣ What is the failure model of an action?

Right now:

  • save/submit mutate runtime

  • DB call happens

  • failure partially rewinds

Q4:
When an action fails, should the FSM:

  • A) fully rollback runtime state

  • B) enter an explicit failure state (save_failed)

  • C) allow partial state (current behavior)

Example:

Code
operation = saving
dirty = true
DB fails
→ what is runtime now?

FSM design depends entirely on this answer.

5️⃣ Are actions persistable or ephemeral?

You hinted at:

actions part of run.input

That’s dangerous unless intentional.

Q5:
Should actions be:

  • A) transient (not serialized, just executed)

  • B) persisted (audit trail / replayable)

  • C) optionally persisted per action

If B, congrats — you’re building event sourcing-lite.
If A, keep them out of run.input.

6️⃣ Is there exactly one FSM per document, or per run?

Right now:

  • run is the unit of truth

  • but documents can live across runs

Q6:
Should the FSM be scoped to:

  • A) a single run (dies when run completes)

  • B) a document instance (survives runs)

  • C) hybrid (document FSM, run FSM)

This decides:

  • where FSM state is stored

  • whether autosave and manual save share logic

7️⃣ Can two actions be concurrent?

Think autosave vs user click submit.

Q7:
Do you allow:

  • autosave running while submit is requested?

  • multiple actions queued?

If no, FSM must serialize actions.
If yes, FSM needs conflict resolution.

Your current operation variable suggests no concurrency, but confirm.

8️⃣ Who owns validation: controller or FSM?

Right now:

  • controller validates schema fields

  • FSM validates transitions

Q8:
Should:

  • schema validation be an FSM guard?

  • or remain in controller pre/post hooks?

Example:

Code
action: submit
guard: schema valid + dirty=false

If FSM owns this → controller becomes thin.
If not → FSM is advisory only.

9️⃣ What is the escape hatch story?

You already have skipController.

Q9:
Do you want:

  • skipFSM

  • forceAction

🧠 TWO FSMs (CLEAN & SMALL)

1️⃣ DocumentFSM (long-lived, authoritative)

JavaScript
class DocumentFSM {
  constructor(initial) {
    this.state = {
      docstatus: initial.docstatus ?? 0,
      lifecycle: "idle", // idle | submitting | failed
      last_error: null,
    };
  }

  apply(action) {
    switch (action.type) {
      case "SUBMIT":
        if (this.state.docstatus !== 0) {
          return this.fail("Cannot submit non-draft document");
        }
        this.state.docstatus = 1;
        this.state.lifecycle = "submitting";
        return ok();

      case "SUBMIT_OK":
        this.state.lifecycle = "idle";
        return ok();

      case "SUBMIT_FAILED":
        this.state.lifecycle = "failed";
        this.state.last_error = action.error;
        return ok();

      default:
        return ok(); // ignore run-level actions
    }
  }

  fail(msg) {
    this.state.lifecycle = "failed";
    this.state.last_error = msg;
    return fail(msg);
  }
}

2️⃣ RunFSM (short-lived, per run)

JavaScript
class RunFSM {
  constructor() {
    this.state = {
      dirty: false,
      operation: "idle", // idle | saving | validating | failed
      last_error: null,
    };
  }

  apply(action) {
    switch (action.type) {
      case "FIELD_CHANGE":
        this.state.dirty = true;
        return ok();

      case "VALIDATE":
        this.state.operation = "validating";
        return ok();

      case "VALIDATE_OK":
        this.state.operation = "idle";
        return ok();

      case "VALIDATE_FAILED":
        this.state.operation = "failed";
        this.state.last_error = action.error;
        return ok();

      case "SAVE":
        if (!this.state.dirty) return fail("Nothing to save");
        this.state.operation = "saving";
        return ok();

      case "SAVE_OK":
        this.state.operation = "idle";
        this.state.dirty = false;
        return ok();

      case "SAVE_FAILED":
        this.state.operation = "failed";
        this.state.last_error = action.error;
        return ok();

      default:
        return ok();
    }
  }
}

🎯 INTENTS → ACTION PLANS

Save intent

JavaScript
const SaveIntent = {
  compile(run, docFSM) {
    return [
      { type: "VALIDATE" },
      { type: "SAVE" },
    ];
  },

Submit intent

JavaScript
const SubmitIntent = {
  compile(run, docFSM) {
    if (run.runFSM.state.operation !== "idle") {
      return [{ type: "WAIT" }];
    }

    return [
      { type: "VALIDATE" },
      { type: "SUBMIT" },
    ];
  },
};

🧩 CONTROLLER (NOW VERY SMALL)

JavaScript
controller.execute = async function (run, intent) {
  const actions = intent.compile(run, run.documentFSM);

  for (const action of actions) {
    persistAction(run, action); // Q9 ✔ per-run trace

    run.runFSM.apply(action);
    run.documentFSM.apply(action);

    if (action.type === "VALIDATE") {
      const result = validateSchema(run);
      if (!result.valid) {
        run.runFSM.apply({ type: "VALIDATE_FAILED", error: result.errors });
        break;
      }
      run.runFSM.apply({ type: "VALIDATE_OK" });
    }

    if (action.type === "SAVE") {
      try {
        await dbSave(run);
        run.runFSM.apply({ type: "SAVE_OK" });
      } catch (e) {
        run.runFSM.apply({ type: "SAVE_FAILED", error: e });
        break;
      }
    }

    if (action.type === "SUBMIT") {
      try {
        await dbSubmit(run);
        run.documentFSM.apply({ type: "SUBMIT_OK" });
      } catch (e) {
        run.documentFSM.apply({ type: "SUBMIT_FAILED", error: e });
        break;
      }
    }
  }

  render(run);
};

Run-based Document Architecture With Fsm + Sfm

Run-Based Document Architecture

This document describes the authoritative architecture for a document-centric system using:

  • Document FSM (long‑lived, persistent meaning)

  • Run FSM (short‑lived execution state)

  • SFM (State Flow Machine) for intent → action sequencing

  • Controller as executor only

  • Per‑run action persistence (execution trace)

This architecture is optimized for:

  • complex document lifecycles (Frappe‑like)

  • autosave + submit correctness

  • debuggability

  • minimal controller complexity

1. Core Concepts

1.1 Document

A Document is the durable business entity persisted in the database.

Examples:

  • Task

  • Invoice

  • Journal Entry

Documents have:

  • schema

  • fields

  • lifecycle constraints (submit, cancel, amend)

Documents do not execute logic.

1.2 Run (Execution Boundary)

A Run represents a single execution session over a document.

Properties:

  • short‑lived

  • owns transient state

  • owns action trace

  • is the only place where mutations happen before DB

A run contains:

  • DocumentFSM

  • RunFSM

  • ActionTrace

Think of a run as a transactional execution bubble.

2. FSM vs SFM (Critical Distinction)

ConceptPurpose
FSMControls state transitions
SFMControls action flow / sequencing

FSM answers:

“Is this transition allowed?”

SFM answers:

“What actions must happen, and in what order?”

They are complementary, not competing.

3. Document FSM (Authoritative Lifecycle)

3.1 Responsibility

The Document FSM owns:

  • docstatus

  • lifecycle legality

  • business‑level failure

It is:

  • deterministic

  • long‑lived

  • independent of UI

3.2 Example States

  • docstatus = 0 → Draft

  • docstatus = 1 → Submitted

  • docstatus = 2 → Cancelled

Optional internal lifecycle:

  • idle

  • submitting

  • failed

3.3 Rules

  • Only DocumentFSM may mutate docstatus

  • Database writes must reflect DocumentFSM state

  • Invalid transitions move to explicit failure state

4. Run FSM (Execution State)

4.1 Responsibility

The Run FSM owns:

  • dirty state

  • operation state

  • validation / save failures

It is:

  • ephemeral

  • reset per run

  • UI‑observable

4.2 Example States

  • dirty: true / false

  • operation:

    • idle

    • validating

    • saving

    • failed

4.3 Rules

  • RunFSM may fail independently of DocumentFSM

  • RunFSM failure does not imply document corruption

  • Autosave logic lives here

5. SFM — State Flow Machine

5.1 Definition

An SFM defines how Intents are compiled into ordered Actions.

It is:

  • stateless

  • deterministic

  • pure logic

SFM never mutates state directly.

5.2 Intent → Action Flow

Example: Submit intent

Intent: SUBMIT
↓
Action Flow:
VALIDATE
(wait for autosave if needed)
SUBMIT

SFM ensures:

  • validation always precedes persistence

  • submit never races autosave

5.3 Why SFM Exists

Without SFM:

  • controllers accumulate branching logic

  • validation becomes duplicated

  • autosave becomes race‑prone

With SFM:

  • flow is declarative

  • controller becomes linear executor

6. Actions

6.1 Definition

An Action is the smallest executable unit.

Properties:

  • typed

  • ordered

  • persisted per run

Examples:

  • FIELD_CHANGE

  • VALIDATE

  • SAVE

  • SUBMIT

6.2 Validation as an Action

Validation is:

  • explicit

  • replayable

  • fail‑able

Validation failures:

  • update RunFSM

  • never partially mutate DB

7. Controller (Executor Only)

7.1 Responsibilities

The controller:

  • receives intent

  • asks SFM for action plan

  • executes actions sequentially

  • persists action trace

7.2 What the Controller Does NOT Do

  • no permission checks

  • no lifecycle decisions

  • no hidden validation

If logic is complex, it does not belong in the controller.

8. Action Persistence (Per Run)

8.1 Why Per‑Run

Per‑run persistence provides:

  • execution trace

  • debuggability

  • auditability

Without event‑sourcing complexity.

8.2 Example Trace

[
VALIDATE,
SAVE,
SAVE_OK
]

Failures are visible and explainable.

9. Autosave + Submit Coordination

9.1 Rule

Submit must wait for autosave completion.

9.2 Enforcement

  • RunFSM exposes operation

  • SFM checks operation before compiling SUBMIT

This prevents race conditions by design.

10. Failure Model (Explicit)

Failures are:

  • states, not booleans

  • observable

  • recoverable

Both FSMs may fail independently.

No silent rollback.

11. UI Binding Model

UI:

  • reads FSM state

  • dispatches intents

UI never:

  • mutates state

  • calls DB

Buttons reflect FSM truth, not heuristics.

12. Key Guarantees

This architecture guarantees:

  • single source of truth

  • no hidden transitions

  • deterministic behavior

  • debuggable runs

  • scalable complexity

13. Mental Model

  • FSM = legality

  • SFM = flow

  • Run = execution

  • Controller = motor

If something feels complex:

it belongs in FSM or SFM — never the controller.

14. Status

This architecture is:

  • complete

  • extensible

  • production‑ready

No further structural decisions are required.

    • not by flags

    • not by timing

    • but by SFM + RunFSM coordination

  • Controller is demoted to a motor
    If your controller grows, it’s a smell — the doc explains why.
